r has made since the brief spike to 162.84 on 30 June. Momentum on the daily timeframe appears to favour the bulls, with price making a fresh near-term high and holding above the prior range ceiling.\n\nThe structure story over the past month is one of persistent compression followed by a decisive resolution to the upside. From late June through to mid-July, USD/JPY oscillated in a relatively tight band between roughly 161.30 and 162.70, with the 162.60\u2013162.70 area acting as a repeated ceiling \u2014 tested and rejected on 1 July, 8 July, and again on 19 July. The break above that prior reaction ceiling on 21 July, and the subsequent ability to hold above 163.00 through the Asian session overnight, suggests the market has absorbed the overhead supply that had accumulated there. To the downside, the nearest meaningful structure support sits in the 160.60 area, a prior reaction zone that attracted four distinct touches during the early-July pullback and has since been left well behind. Deeper zones cluster around 159.87 and 159.61, but these feel distant given current positioning.\n\nOn the H1 chart, the intraday read is one of measured consolidation after a sharp overnight advance. Price pushed from 162.50 at the start of the 21 July London afternoon session to a high of 163.25 in the early hours of 22 July \u2014 a clean, almost uninterrupted grind higher across roughly 12 hourly candles. Since that peak, the pair has drifted modestly lower, trading in a narrow 163.04\u2013163.25 band. The hourly structure shows no aggressive selling; rather, the pullback looks corrective in nature, with each dip finding buyers relatively quickly. The 163.00 level \u2014 which coincided with the early-morning breakout candle \u2014 now represents the immediate intraday reference point that bulls will want to see defended.\n\nThe economic calendar carries no scheduled data releases of note today, which removes a key source of near-term volatility. In the absence of macro catalysts, price action is likely to remain technically driven, with positioning and broader risk sentiment the primary movers.\n\nWhat would alter the bullish read? A sustained hourly close back beneath 163.00 would introduce caution, and a return into the 162.50\u2013162.65 congestion zone \u2014 the prior ceiling now acting as prospective support \u2014 would meaningfully weaken the near-term case. A daily close back below 162.40 would suggest the breakout attempt has failed.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}